  "prompt": "Why do cats spit hairballs? Is it harmful?",
  "response": "Cats spit up hairballs as a result of grooming themselves. When a cat licks its fur, the tiny, hook-like structures on their tongue catch loose and dead hair. Most of this hair passes through the digestive system without issue. However, some hair can accumulate in the stomach and form a hairball, which the cat will eventually cough up as a protective reflex to prevent the hair from causing an intestinal blockage.\n\nOccasional hairballs are generally normal for cats and not usually harmful. However, frequent or excessive hairballs can sometimes indicate underlying issues, such as skin disorders, over-grooming due to stress, or gastrointestinal problems. There are also rare instances where a hairball can lead to an obstruction in the digestive tract, which can be serious and require veterinary attention.\n\nIf a cat is having frequent hairballs or seems to be in distress when trying to expel them, it's a good idea to consult a veterinarian. They can help determine if there are underlying issues that need addressing and recommend preventative measures such as diet changes, grooming routines, or other appropriate interventions.",
